TY  - JOUR
AU  - Giannetti, Mariassunta
AU  - Liao, Guanmin
AU  - You, Jiaxing
AU  - Yu, Xiaoyun
T1  - The Externalities of Corruption: Evidence from Entrepreneurial Firms in China*
PY  - 2021
Y1  - 2021/05/01
DO  - 10.1093/rof/rfaa038
JO  - Review of Finance
JA  - Rev Financ
VL  - 25
IS  - 3
SP  - 629
EP  - 667
SN  - 1572-3097
AB  - Exploiting China’s anti-corruption campaign, we show that following a decrease in corruption, firm performance improves. Small and young firms benefit more. We identify the channels through which corruption hampers firm performance. Following the anti-corruption campaign, the allocation of capital and labor becomes more efficient. Firms operating in ex ante more corrupt environments experience larger productivity gains, higher growth of sales, and lower cost of debt than other firms. Taken together, our results suggest that corruption is an inefficient equilibrium for an economy because it creates negative externalities.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rof/rfaa038
ER  - 



