TY  - JOUR
AU  - Charoenwong, Ben
AU  - Morck, Randall
AU  - Wiwattanakantang, Yupana
T1  - Bank of Japan Equity Purchases: The (Non-)Effects of Extreme Quantitative Easing*
PY  - 2021
Y1  - 2021/05/01
DO  - 10.1093/rof/rfaa029
JO  - Review of Finance
JA  - Rev Financ
VL  - 25
IS  - 3
SP  - 713
EP  - 743
SN  - 1572-3097
AB  - From January 2011 through March 2018, the Bank of Japan purchased equity index exchange-traded funds (ETFs) worth about 3.5% of GDP. Identification of the effect of central bank ETF purchases on stock valuations and corporate responses is via differently-weighted and changing stock indices. BOJ purchases lift valuations, increase share issuances, and increase total assets. On average, the latter increase is due to cash and short-term securities rather than capital investment. However, firms with worse corporate governance do increase capital investment. These findings suggest central bank equity purchases are a problematic tool for stimulating economic growth through high broad-based private-sector corporate investment.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rof/rfaa029
ER  - 



